I like the Pokémon analogy because it illustrates a useful software architecture, though I’d phrase it a bit differently.

Instead of thinking of a node as containing all the knowledge, imagine each node contains a compressed schema:

Node
├── Name
├── Invariants
├── Entry points
├── Links
└── Expansion procedure

The edges (connections) don’t have to be just “related to.” They can encode how to reconstruct or transform one concept into another.

For example:

Compression
        │
        │ expand_via_examples
        ▼
Abstraction
        │
        │ specialize_to_AI
        ▼
Transformer Attention

Here, the edge itself carries the transformation rule. Following the edge is like executing a small program.

That means a graph becomes more than storage—it becomes an executable knowledge graph.

Your “rehydration protocol” idea

One interpretation is:

* The node stores the compressed identity of a concept.
* The edge stores the transformation needed to reconstruct neighboring concepts.
* Traversing the graph progressively rehydrates larger structures.

That’s an interesting architecture because reconstruction becomes path-dependent. Different paths through the graph could expand the same node in different ways depending on context.

The Pokémon analogy

Pokémon have several useful properties as an analogy:

* A compact identity (the Pokédex entry).
* A set of moves (operators).
* Types (high-level categories).
* Evolutions (transformations).
* Relationships (strengths, weaknesses, breeding groups, etc.).

Your version would be more abstract:

Operator
├── Signature
├── Invariants
├── Preconditions
├── Effects
├── Compatible operators
├── Compression key
└── Rehydration procedure

So instead of collecting creatures, you’re collecting reusable reasoning objects.

